    "body": "followup to https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/37971\r\n\r\n## Problem\r\n\r\nOld 'autoread' only did `:checktime` on focus-change and shell (\":!\") commands, and only for non-hidden buffers. Since 'autoread' is now driven by OS filewatcher events, buffers are updated much more eagerly. This should be surfaced to the user somehow, either via a carefully placed notification, or a minimal UI indicator.\r\n\r\nA \"notification\" would be noisy, unless it is conditional on specific circumstances (e.g. when \"many\" buffers are updated).\r\n\r\n\r\n## Solution\r\nUse the existing buffer-local 'busy' option as a subtle hint about activity.\r\n\r\n## Interactive demo\r\n\r\n```sh\r\necho initial > /tmp/busy.txt &&     ( sleep 2; for i in 1 2 3; do echo \"external $i\" >> /tmp/busy.txt; sleep 1; done ) &     VIMRUNTIME=\"$(pwd)/runtime\" ./build/bin/nvim --luamod-dev -c 'lua require(\"nvim.autoread\")._set_debounce(100)' /tmp/busy.txt\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/1c0eb1fd-3a80-41f8-9fc4-dee60671b647\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## Todo\r\n\r\nNeed to try this out and see how useful it is in practice. The implementation itself is harmless, except for the extra bit of code. But if it turns out to be useless then we can revisit.",
